==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fastidious
<hw>Fas*tid"i*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>fastidiosus</ets> disdainful, fr. <ets>fastidium</ets> loathing,
aversion, perh. fr. <ets>fastus</ets> arrogance (of uncertain origin) +
<ets>taedium</ets> loathing. Cf. <er>Tedious</er>, <er>Fash</er>.]</ety>
<def>Difficult to please; delicate to a fault; suited with difficulty;
squeamish; <as>as, a <ex>fastidious</ex> mind or ear; a
<ex>fastidious</ex> appetite.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Proud youth ! <qex>fastidious</qex> of the lower world.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Squeamish; critical; overnice; difficult;
punctilious.</syn> -- <usage><er>Fastidious</er>, <er>Squeamish</er>. We
call a person <xex>fastidious</xex> when his taste or feelings are
offended by trifling defects or errors; we call him <xex>squeamish</xex>
when he is excessively nice or critical on minor points, and also when
he is overscrupulous as to questions of duty. ⟦ldquo⟧Whoever examines
his own imperfections will cease to be <xex>fastidious</xex>; whoever
restrains his caprice and scrupulosity will cease to be
<xex>squeamish</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Crabb.</au></usage></p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Fas*tid"i*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Fas*tid"i*ous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms></p>

<p><ent>Fastigiated</ent>⟦br⟧
